"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Written evidence from the Motor Accident Solicitors Society (MASS) (CMI0028)&#xa0;Summary&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nComments on the TSC Letter to the Ministry of Justice&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Additional IssuesWe agree consideration should be given to better information sharing\n and MASS has been in discussions with the ABI for over two years to \nfind \nagreement on what data can be shared with claimant solicitors at an early\n stage. \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nO\nne issue on transparency \nworthy of consideration is \naround the starting of new policies. Our understanding is that when a new policy is created through a ‘broker’ (such as gocompare) the insurer has little opportunity to cancel the policy \nif there are fraudulent aspects,\n before the expiry of the 14 day canc\nellation period.  We would suggest that this element needs to be investigated further in order to stop fraud at the instigation of the policy\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Additional Comments on the Governments Response&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDecember 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n"